, Nancy Bauer discusses practices such as recycling plant waste on site, using permeable pathways, growing regionally appropriate plants, and avoiding chemical fertilizers and insecticides. She suggests ways of attracting pollinators through planting choices and offers ideas for building water sources and shelters for wildlife. A plant resource guide, tips for propagating plants, seasonal plants for hummingbirds, and host plants for butterflies round out The California Wildlife Habitat Garden, making it an indispensable primer for those about to embark on creating their own biologically diverse, environmentally friendly garden.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGardening to attract birdszCalifornia. 0aGardening to attract wildlifezCalifornia. 7aNATURE / Plants / General.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  aamerican gardening.  abooks about wildlife.  abooks for animal lovers.  acaring for wild life.  acoffee table books.  acreating your own ecosystem.  aenvironmental ecosystems.  afixing your garden.  agardening and horticulture landscape.  agardening for dummies.  ahome school science books.  ahow to garden.  aideas for quarantine.  aliving ecosystems.  aplants and wildlife.  aprotecting wildlife.  athings to do when youre bored.  atransform backyard.  awest region gardening.  awhat seeds should i plant.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026781740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095350540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520953505/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY